Ahh, now I understand. You're asking:

> "How would I do this entire `Student`, `Comparable`, `Comparator`, `sort by name`, `sort by roll_num`, `sort by cgpa` thing in JavaScript?"

### Java

```java
Collections.sort(list);
```

works because you implemented:

```java
public int compareTo(Student s){
    return this.name.compareTo(s.name);
}
```

JavaScript has **no Comparable interface**.

Instead, you pass the comparison function directly into `sort()`.

---

## JavaScript Version

```js
function Student(name, roll_num, cgpa) {
    this.name = name;
    this.roll_num = roll_num;
    this.cgpa = cgpa;
}

const a = new Student("kalpesh", 5, 9);
const b = new Student("tejas", 4, 10);
const c = new Student("om", 1, 11);
const d = new Student("nishant", 2, 13);
const e = new Student("ayush", 3, 12);

const list = [a, b, c, d, e];
```

---

## Sort by Name

Java:

```java
Collections.sort(list);
```

JavaScript:

```js
list.sort((s1, s2) => s1.name.localeCompare(s2.name));
```

Output:

```text
ayush
kalpesh
nishant
om
tejas
```

---

## Sort by Roll Number

Java:

```java
list.sort(Comparator.comparingInt(s -> s.roll_num));
```

JavaScript:

```js
list.sort((s1, s2) => s1.roll_num - s2.roll_num);
```

Output:

```text
om
nishant
ayush
tejas
kalpesh
```

---

## Sort by Roll Number Descending

Java:

```java
Integer.compare(s2.roll_num, s1.roll_num)
```

JavaScript:

```js
list.sort((s1, s2) => s2.roll_num - s1.roll_num);
```

Output:

```text
kalpesh
tejas
ayush
nishant
om
```

---

## Sort by CGPA

```js
list.sort((s1, s2) => s1.cgpa - s2.cgpa);
```

---

## Sort by Name then CGPA

Java:

```java
Comparator.comparing((Student s) -> s.name)
          .thenComparingInt(s -> s.cgpa)
```

JavaScript:

```js
list.sort((s1, s2) => {
    if (s1.name !== s2.name) {
        return s1.name.localeCompare(s2.name);
    }

    return s1.cgpa - s2.cgpa;
});
```

Think:

```text
Compare names first.

Same name?
    Compare cgpa.
Different?
    Stop there.
```

---

## Sort by Name then CGPA then Roll Number

Java:

```java
.thenComparingInt(s -> s.cgpa)
.thenComparingInt(s -> s.roll_num)
```

JavaScript:

```js
list.sort((s1, s2) => {

    if (s1.name !== s2.name) {
        return s1.name.localeCompare(s2.name);
    }

    if (s1.cgpa !== s2.cgpa) {
        return s1.cgpa - s2.cgpa;
    }

    return s1.roll_num - s2.roll_num;
});
```

---

### Funny Translation

Java says:

```java
Student implements Comparable<Student>
```

JavaScript says:

```js
Bro, just give me the comparison function when you sort.
```

So instead of storing the comparison rule inside the class (`compareTo`), JavaScript usually puts the comparison rule directly inside:

```js
array.sort((a, b) => ...)
```

That's the biggest difference. Java likes comparison logic inside the class (`Comparable`), while JavaScript usually passes it directly to `sort()`. 🚀
